value: The strategy was for X to be aggressive and always force O into a defensive move
I made X go on defense by finding moves for O that X had to block every time or lose

You have to stop blue from making the diagonal win first, at which point the board shows a scenario where you have a chance to place a true winning move where the opponent can make their ideal move and still lose.
e8 wouldnt win because it leaves only one option to block for O
I played the next moves for X to try and win, and tried to make the best move possible for O to counter, and the suggested move did not produce a win.
I defended the move which gave opening to position for the ultimate win, when O tried to take its move.

I wanted to build up a scaffold of either O's so that I could guarantee an X win and leave O with little choice but to do what it had to do. Honesty hour? I really couldn't separate myself into two entities playing against each other. Every move was a challenge NOT to be one sided.
I put a circle to block x's win and it proved that it wasn't a winning move.
I played through the options on both sides in my head, each time playing to win as both O and X. Once I found a series of plays for O that could beat X, I stopped.
Its' O turn to play and will mostly play in the spot that guarantees X not to win.
placed an x in the desired location then tried to block x's win with an o and found out that no matter what o did x would win in the next move\n
Process of elimination, O can block X on one side and X would only have 4 in a row
I tried to spread out as much as possible to provide numerous opportunities to win.
If you can get 4 x's in a row with an open square on each side its a guaranteed victory.
If an x is placed on a side of the board that may seem to be the start of a winning game, the person playing o may follow, giving x the chance to choose the winning move anyway.
Make moves that will force O into a defensive posture, leaving openings for X to play offensively.

I determined what moves had to be made and then used trial and error from there. Some moves would guarantee a win unless blue retaliated so those were prioritized. Then I played around with other moves to see if any would work.
I placed an o in the most strategic spots to attempt to counter x by determining the most immediate threat, and placed x's accordingly until it would win no matter what o did to counter.
I played the match out in multiple ways. If the O player blocked the X player from winning diagonally e8 would not be considered a guaranteed win.

I tried different ways of thinking like O to beat X and vice-versa. Once I figured out a way that X had the advantage and O would have to block to stop X, it took several moves, and I eventually got to a place where O would not be able to win. It did take me several tries to figure it out. And then I repeated the pattern several more times to make sure I was correct.

The position chosen was a winning spot. Once O covered the 5x's I was able to put it below where there was 3 x's already. So putting another X made it 4 in a row. So O was forced to used their next move to stop my X's. Then right above that was 3 X's going horizontally. So once my 5 X attempt was blocked, I setup the 4X horizontal right above. This was a guaranteed win since O couldn't block both ends of this horizontal 4 X. They placed an O on one side, and I placed my X on the other.
